expertise_classifications.author: robobun
expertise_signals: Replaced a polling-style while loop with an event-driven Promise pattern to eliminate flakiness from timing issues
Checks already-buffered messages before subscribing to new ones, avoiding a race condition where the final render arrives before the listener is attached
Understands that HMR watcher coalescing can skip intermediate renders and cause duplicate final renders, draining the buffer accordingly
Properly cleans up the event listener in both resolve and reject paths to prevent leaks
expertise_classifications.summary: Deflakes an HMR rapid-edits test by replacing a sequential polling loop with an event-driven approach that handles race conditions, message buffering, and watcher coalescing — showing deep understanding of async test reliability and HMR behavior.

expertise_classifications.author: sosukesuzuki
expertise_signals: Understands that JIT compilers can emit CPU instructions (AVX, LSE) not available on baseline targets, and uses QEMU to catch this at CI time
Carefully selects CPU models (Nehalem for x64 SSE4.2 baseline, Cortex-A53 for ARMv8.0-A) that match the project's actual minimum hardware targets
Distinguishes SIGILL (exit code 132) from other test failures to separate CPU instruction issues from unrelated test problems
Integrates conditionally into the CI pipeline only when SetupWebKit.cmake changes, showing understanding of when JIT codegen regressions can be introduced
expertise_classifications.summary: Adds conditional QEMU-based JIT stress testing to CI that runs when WebKit is updated, catching JIT-generated code that uses CPU instructions beyond baseline targets — demonstrating deep understanding of JIT compilation risks, CPU feature levels, and CI architecture.

expertise_classifications.author: robobun
expertise_signals: Identified a missing reference count increment (incPendingActivityCount) in a specific code path that leads to premature GC and a 'pure virtual function called' crash
Understands the interaction between postTask deferred execution, garbage collection, and WebSocket lifecycle management
Recognized that the blob binaryType path was missing the incPendingActivityCount that other similar paths likely already had
Wrote a precise regression test that reproduces the race condition by creating unreferenced WebSocket objects and forcing GC while postTask callbacks are pending
expertise_classifications.summary: Fixes a use-after-free crash in the WebSocket blob binary data path by adding a missing incPendingActivityCount() call that prevents GC from collecting the WebSocket before its deferred postTask callback executes, demonstrating deep understanding of the GC/reference-counting lifecycle in the bindings layer.

expertise_classifications.author: Jarred-Sumner
expertise_signals: Designed a new multi_run.zig module (838 lines) with process lifecycle management, integrating into the existing ProcessExitHandler tagged union dispatch system
Extended the CLI argument parsing pipeline across Arguments.zig, cli.zig, and Command context to thread new flags through the entire initialization path

Integrated with bun's internal process management by adding a new MultiRunProcessHandle variant to the ProcessExitHandler tagged pointer dispatch, showing deep understanding of the runtime's process model
Comprehensive test suite (2023 lines) covering parallel/sequential execution, workspace filtering, error handling modes, glob patterns, and prefixed output formatting
expertise_classifications.summary: Adds a complete parallel/sequential multi-script execution system with Foreman-style output, workspace integration, and process lifecycle management, demonstrating architect-level understanding of bun's CLI pipeline, process model, and workspace infrastructure.

expertise_classifications.author: prekucki
expertise_signals: Uses Symbol.for to persist the pending scripts map across HMR runtime re-evaluations, preventing state loss during rapid updates
Changes from a simple single-entry Map to a queue (array per key) to handle multiple in-flight HMR scripts for the same module, addressing a race condition
Thorough regression test that patches both error handlers and the HMR callback itself to detect 'Unknown HMR script' errors that would otherwise be swallowed
Understands the timing relationship between script tag creation/execution and the bun:hmr callback, recognizing that multiple scripts can be pending before any execute
expertise_classifications.summary: Fixes a race condition where rapid consecutive HMR updates caused 'Unknown HMR script' errors by converting the script tracking from a single-entry map to a per-module queue with cross-evaluation persistence, demonstrating deep understanding of the HMR script lifecycle and browser execution timing.

expertise_classifications.author: robobun
expertise_signals: Identifies HTTP header injection vulnerability via CRLF in user-controlled header values (contentDisposition, contentType, contentEncoding)
Places validation at the correct point in the parsing flow—after UTF8 conversion but before assignment to the credentials struct
Comprehensive regression tests covering CRLF, CR-only, LF-only, and valid (non-injecting) inputs
Uses std.mem.indexOfAny for efficient character scanning in Zig
expertise_classifications.summary: Security fix that rejects CRLF characters in S3 header value options to prevent HTTP header injection, with thorough regression tests covering all three affected fields and edge cases—showing solid understanding of the vulnerability and codebase but following a straightforward validation pattern.

expertise_classifications.author: cirospaciari
expertise_signals: Correctly identifies that proxy-style absolute URLs (http://...) in the request line were being conflated with CONNECT tunnel mode, causing keep-alive connections to hang on subsequent requests
Separates the isConnect and isProxyStyleURL conditions in the HTTP parser to prevent tunnel mode from being entered for non-CONNECT proxy requests
Uses a shared agent with maxSockets:1 in tests to force connection reuse, which is the exact scenario needed to reproduce the keep-alive bug
Tests are designed to run on both Node.js and Bun, validating behavioral parity with the reference implementation
expertise_classifications.summary: Fixes the HTTP parser to distinguish proxy-style absolute URLs from CONNECT requests, preventing the server from incorrectly entering tunnel mode and hanging on subsequent keep-alive requests — demonstrating deep understanding of HTTP parsing state transitions and proxy protocol semantics.

expertise_classifications.author: sosukesuzuki
expertise_signals: Ported JSC JIT stress tests (DFG, FTL, WASM tiers) from WebKit, demonstrating understanding of which JIT compiler stages need regression coverage in Bun
Created a test harness (jsc-stress.test.ts + preload.js) that adapts WebKit's testing conventions (like $vm, noInline) to Bun's test runner
Used bunfig.toml with preload to inject WebKit-style test helpers, showing knowledge of Bun's configuration system
Selected tests targeting specific JIT edge cases: OSR entry/exit, try-catch value recovery, register allocation, tail-call clobbering pinned registers — indicating awareness of JSC internals
expertise_classifications.summary: Ports ~80 WebKit JSC JIT stress tests covering DFG, FTL, and WASM compiler tiers into Bun's test suite with a custom harness, demonstrating deep knowledge of JSC JIT internals and which edge cases matter for Bun's compatibility.

expertise_classifications.author: dylan-conway
expertise_signals: Identified a use-after-free caused by a race between output_waiting and output_done counters — output_waiting was only incremented in the async (needsIO) branch, but output_done was always incremented, causing premature done()/free
The fix moves the counter increment before the conditional branch so it is always balanced with output_done, regardless of sync vs async write path
Applied the same fix consistently across all four affected builtins (cp, ls, mkdir, touch), showing understanding of the shared OutputTask pattern
Test specifically targets the ASAN-detectable use-after-poison scenario using command substitution $() which forces pipe (sync) stdout, demonstrating understanding of the exact triggering conditions
expertise_classifications.summary: Fixes a use-after-free in shell builtin OutputTask callbacks by ensuring the output_waiting counter is always incremented regardless of sync/async write path, preventing premature deallocation when builtins run inside command substitution — this demonstrates deep understanding of the async I/O lifecycle and failure modes in the shell execution engine.

expertise_classifications.author: Jarred-Sumner
expertise_signals: Implements TC39 standard ES decorators lowering from scratch (~1500 lines in lowerDecorators.zig), requiring deep understanding of the JavaScript specification's decorator semantics including auto-accessors, private fields, static blocks, and decorator evaluation order

Carefully integrates the new lowering pass across the entire transpiler pipeline: parser (parseStmt, parsePrefix, parseProperty, parseTypescript), visitor (visitStmt, visitExpr, visitBinaryExpression), printer, module loader, bundler, and resolver/tsconfig

Handles complex edge cases like anonymous decorated class expressions needing names from assignment context (decorator_class_name field), private member lowering with storage refs/getter/setter function refs, and correct interleaving of static initializers with class static blocks

Adds runtime support functions (__esDecorate, __esRunInitializers, __esParam) in both runtime.js and runtime.zig, plus comprehensive test coverage including ported esbuild decorator tests (~3900 lines of test fixtures)
expertise_classifications.summary: Implements TC39 standard ES decorators lowering as a new transpiler pass touching parsing, visiting, printing, runtime helpers, and resolver/tsconfig integration, demonstrating architect-level understanding of the entire compilation pipeline and the decorator specification's complex semantics.

expertise_classifications.author: robobun
expertise_signals: Simple snapshot string updates to match new Redis 8 error message format
No logic changes, only updating expected error message strings
Mechanical removal of trailing ', with args beginning with: ' from error snapshots
expertise_classifications.summary: Updates inline test snapshots to match Redis 8's shorter error message format, a straightforward mechanical change requiring no deep understanding.

expertise_classifications.author: robobun
expertise_signals: Handles all edge cases of partial chunk terminator reads (remaining == 0, 1, 2, >2) showing understanding of streaming parser state machines
Validates terminator bytes eagerly during partial consumption to prevent request smuggling attacks
Understands that chunkSize includes the +2 terminator bytes and accounts for split reads across the terminator boundary
Tests cover fragmented TCP delivery where \r and \n arrive in separate packets, which is a subtle real-world networking edge case
expertise_classifications.summary: Hardens the chunked transfer encoding parser to validate chunk terminators even when they arrive split across TCP reads, preventing request smuggling — demonstrating deep understanding of streaming parser state machines and HTTP security edge cases.

expertise_classifications.author: dylan-conway
expertise_signals: Chose specific CPU models (Nehalem for x64 baseline with SSE4.2/no AVX, Cortex-A53 for ARMv8.0-A/no LSE/SVE) that precisely match the project's baseline CPU targets

Used QEMU user-mode emulation as a CI verification strategy to catch illegal instructions (SIGILL/exit code 132) rather than static analysis — a non-obvious approach showing understanding of binary verification techniques

Correctly integrated the verification step into the existing CI pipeline topology with proper dependency chains, artifact naming conventions (matching cmake/targets/BuildBun.cmake), and agent selection
Handles both static and dynamic QEMU binaries, and verifies both the release binary and the profile binary, showing awareness of all build artifacts that need validation
expertise_classifications.summary: Adds QEMU user-mode CI verification to catch forbidden CPU instructions (AVX/LSE/SVE) in baseline builds, demonstrating deep understanding of the project's cross-platform CPU targeting constraints and CI architecture.

expertise_classifications.author: robobun
expertise_signals: Updated NSS root certificates from a previous version to NSS 3.119, removing revoked/deprecated CommScope and other certificates
Systematically replaced external HTTPS endpoints in tests with localhost/local server alternatives to eliminate flaky external dependencies
Modified test assertions and setup across multiple test files to use local HTTP servers instead of external URLs like example.com, httpbin.org
Maintained test coverage intent while changing test infrastructure - e.g., replacing external fetch targets with local echo servers
expertise_classifications.summary: Updates root certificate bundle to NSS 3.119 (removing deprecated CommScope certs) and replaces external HTTPS calls in tests with local servers, showing solid understanding of test reliability and certificate management but following established patterns.

expertise_classifications.author: sosukesuzuki
expertise_signals: Implements int32 fast path with separate adjustSliceOffsetInt32/Double functions to avoid unnecessary double conversions in the hot path
Correctly handles edge cases: NaN → 0, negative offsets clamped, detached buffer checks, resizable/growable shared buffer distinction with different structures

Understands JSC internals: uses IDLOperation, DECLARE_THROW_SCOPE, RETURN_IF_EXCEPTION, possiblySharedBuffer, byteOffset composition, and appropriate subclass structures (JSBufferSubclassStructure vs JSResizableOrGrowableSharedBufferSubclassStructure)
Moves from JS builtin to native C++ with ALWAYS_INLINE helpers, showing understanding of where JS-to-native boundary optimization matters most for a hot function like Buffer.slice
expertise_classifications.summary: Moves Buffer.slice/subarray from JS builtins to native C++ with an int32 fast path, demonstrating deep understanding of JSC engine internals, TypedArray edge cases (detached buffers, resizable arrays, NaN handling), and performance-critical code paths.

expertise_classifications.author: robobun
expertise_signals: Adds a 731-line MetafileBuilder.zig that generates structured markdown bundle analysis from internal linker data structures, showing deep understanding of the bundler's chunk/part/source graph model

Extends the metafile API surface across multiple language boundaries (Zig, C++, JavaScript/TypeScript) consistently, handling JS API polymorphism (boolean | string | object) with proper memory management
Correctly propagates the new output kinds through standalone mode checks (isFileInStandaloneMode) and production build paths (bake/production.zig), showing awareness of cross-cutting concerns
Comprehensive test suite (722+ lines) covering CLI flags, JS API variations, markdown output format validation, and edge cases like multiple entry points and CSS chunking
expertise_classifications.summary: Adds a comprehensive --metafile-md CLI option and extended JS API for generating LLM-friendly markdown bundle analysis, requiring deep understanding of the bundler's linker internals, cross-language bindings, and output pipeline to correctly generate structured markdown from chunk/module graph data.

expertise_classifications.author: robobun
expertise_signals: Understands that null bytes act as field terminators in both MySQL and PostgreSQL wire protocols, enabling parameter injection attacks
Properly handles resource cleanup (options_buf, tls_config, tls_ctx) before returning the error to prevent memory leaks
Uses Zig's `inline for` with compile-time string concatenation (`entry[1] ++ " must not contain null bytes"`) for DRY validation across multiple fields
Test suite verifies the fix at the protocol level using mock TCP servers, confirming no data is sent before rejection (serverReceivedData === false)
expertise_classifications.summary: Security fix preventing null byte injection in SQL connection parameters for both MySQL and PostgreSQL wire protocols, demonstrating deep understanding of protocol-level vulnerabilities, proper resource cleanup in the Zig codebase, and thorough regression testing.

expertise_classifications.author: dylan-conway
expertise_signals: Adds Windows ARM64 cross-compilation support with specific toolchain flags (--toolchain windows-aarch64, -DSKIP_CODEGEN=ON, clang-cl compilers), showing understanding of cross-compilation constraints
Fixes C++ source code to be compatible with LLVM 21 (e.g., std::optional changes in URLPatternParser, constexpr additions in EncodingTables.h, updated SIMD intrinsics in highway_strings.cpp)
Handles platform-specific agent routing: cross-compiles Windows aarch64 from x64 runners rather than requiring native ARM64 Windows CI machines
Updates multiple build infrastructure layers in coordination: Dockerfile, CI pipeline, CMake, Nix flakes, bootstrap scripts, and source-level compiler compatibility fixes
expertise_classifications.summary: Upgrades the entire LLVM toolchain from 19.1.7 to 21.1.8 across CI, build system, and source code while simultaneously enabling Windows ARM64 cross-compilation, demonstrating deep understanding of the build infrastructure, compiler compatibility requirements, and cross-platform concerns.

expertise_classifications.author: robobun
expertise_signals: Identified a use-after-free / dangling pointer bug: delete without nulling the pointer
Understands C++ memory management pattern of setting deleted pointers to nullptr to prevent double-free or dangling access
Targeted fix in the correct location (clearAll cleanup path) suggesting understanding of the plugin lifecycle
expertise_classifications.summary: Fixes a dangling pointer bug by setting virtualModules to nullptr after deletion in the plugin clear function, showing understanding of C++ memory safety patterns.

expertise_classifications.author: Jarred-Sumner
expertise_signals: Designed and implemented an entire Markdown parser from scratch in Zig (src/md/) with 14+ modules covering blocks, inlines, containers, autolinks, entities, unicode, ref_defs, link resolution, and HTML rendering

Integrated the parser across multiple system layers: Zig parser core, C++ JSC bindings (JSReactElement), JavaScript API surface (BunObject/MarkdownObject), bundler integration (ParseTask, transpiler), and module loader

Created a comprehensive public API with three rendering modes (html, render callbacks, React JSX) including JSReactElement C++ bindings for zero-copy React element creation directly from the native layer

Extensive spec-compliance testing with CommonMark spec.txt (9756 lines), GFM extensions, edge cases, regressions, and multiple test suites covering HTML output, React rendering, and callback-based rendering
expertise_classifications.summary: Architect-level addition of a complete Markdown parser written in Zig with full GFM support, integrated across the native parser, C++ JSC bindings (including custom JSReactElement), JavaScript API surface, bundler pipeline, TypeScript types, documentation, and comprehensive spec-compliance test suites.

expertise_classifications.author: dylan-conway
expertise_signals: Renamed CatchScope to TopExceptionScope across 71 files, tracking an upstream WebKit API rename with precision
Added bmalloc.lib linking requirement for Windows builds, indicating understanding of WebKit's memory allocator dependency changes
Changed USE_MIMALLOC to USE_BUN_MIMALLOC to avoid conflicts with upstream WebKit's own USE_MIMALLOC definition
Updated JSDOMPromiseDeferred.h to change exception handling patterns (CatchScope → TopExceptionScope) in templated promise resolution code
expertise_classifications.summary: Updates the vendored WebKit dependency to a new version, adapting to the upstream rename of CatchScope to TopExceptionScope and build system changes (bmalloc linkage, macro rename), demonstrating deep understanding of how Bun integrates with JavaScriptCore internals.

expertise_classifications.author: alii
expertise_signals: Introduces an entirely new ESM bytecode compilation pipeline spanning 37 files across bundler, runtime, linker, standalone module graph, and C++ bindings
Created a new analyze_transpiled_module.zig (513 lines) that performs deep analysis of transpiled ESM modules for bytecode generation, showing understanding of JS module semantics
Modified the bytecode caching system (RuntimeTranspilerCache.zig) to handle ESM module info alongside bytecode, understanding cache invalidation and alignment requirements
Coordinated changes across Zig/C++ boundary (BunAnalyzeTranspiledModule.cpp, ZigSourceProvider.cpp, headers-handwritten.h) showing full-stack understanding of Bun's architecture
expertise_classifications.summary: Implements ESM bytecode compilation support across the entire pipeline—bundler, linker, runtime loader, standalone graph, and C++ bindings—introducing new module analysis infrastructure and coordinating cross-cutting concerns like bytecode origin paths, module info metadata, and cache alignment, demonstrating architect-level system design.

expertise_classifications.author: dylan-conway
expertise_signals: Built a complete JSON5 parser from scratch in Zig (913-line interchange/json5.zig) with proper handling of hex literals, single-quoted strings, multiline strings, comments, trailing commas, and Unicode escapes
Integrated the parser across multiple system layers: module loader, bundler linker, transpiler, DevServer watch store, and exposed it as a Bun.JSON5 API with JSC bindings

Followed and extended existing architectural patterns (mirroring YAMLObject.zig structure for JSON5Object.zig, adding to the interchange module, extending the loader enum consistently across schema.zig/options.zig/ParseTask.zig)
Comprehensive test suite with 2500+ lines including a generated test suite from the JSON5 spec, edge cases for Unicode, numeric edge cases (Infinity, NaN, hex), and error handling validation
expertise_classifications.summary: Implements a complete native JSON5 parser in Zig, integrates it across the module loader, bundler, and runtime API surface, and exposes it as Bun.JSON5 — demonstrating architect-level understanding of Bun's loader pipeline, JSC binding layer, and interchange module architecture.

expertise_classifications.author: chrislloyd
expertise_signals: Understands JSC VM internals: uses vm.propertyNames->disposeSymbol to register a well-known symbol on the prototype
Reuses the existing mockRestore function reference from the prototype rather than creating a new wrapper, showing awareness of JSC object layout
Correctly sets PropertyAttribute::Function | PropertyAttribute::DontEnum to match Symbol.dispose conventions
Tests cover multiple usage patterns (spyOn, mock(), prototype methods) and verify auto-restore semantics via block-scoped `using`
expertise_classifications.summary: Adds Symbol.dispose support to mock/spyOn by wiring the dispose symbol to mockRestore on the JSMockFunction prototype in JSC, demonstrating understanding of the VM's symbol property machinery and the TC39 explicit resource management protocol.

expertise_classifications.author: alii
expertise_signals: Correctly threads the --retry flag through CLI parsing (cli.zig, Arguments.zig), config (bunfig.zig), and test execution (Execution.zig, ScopeFunctions.zig)
Modifies the Zig test execution logic to track retry counts and emit separate JUnit XML testcase entries for each retry attempt
Comprehensive test coverage with retry-flag.test.ts (315 lines) covering CLI flag, bunfig config, per-test override, and JUnit XML output
Updates documentation, completions, and configuration in a cohesive manner across the full stack
expertise_classifications.summary: Adds a --retry flag for test retries with proper threading through CLI parsing, bunfig config, Zig test execution, and JUnit XML reporting, demonstrating working-level understanding of how the test runner pipeline is structured end-to-end.

expertise_classifications.author: sosukesuzuki
expertise_signals: Adds a new DenseArray fast path variant with proper shared-reference detection (seenObjects HashSet) to prevent incorrect cloning of aliased objects
Uses std::variant-based DenseArrayElement type with WTF::makeVisitor for memory cost computation, showing familiarity with WebKit/Bun's type patterns
Correctly handles edge cases: holes in arrays, Symbol/BigInt fallback, circular reference detection, exception propagation with RETURN_IF_EXCEPTION
Integrates with existing fast-path architecture (FastPath enum, SimpleCloneableObject, isObjectFastPathCandidate) rather than creating parallel abstractions
expertise_classifications.summary: Extends the structuredClone fast path to handle arrays containing simple objects by adding a DenseArray variant with proper shared-reference detection, edge case handling, and comprehensive tests, demonstrating deep understanding of the serialization architecture and JavaScript value semantics.

expertise_classifications.author: cirospaciari
expertise_signals: Introduced a new SocketMode enum abstraction replacing the boolean is_server flag, adding duplex_server mode to handle TLS upgrade lifecycle differences between listener-owned servers and duplex-upgraded connections
Created a complete _http2_upgrade.ts module (~395 lines) implementing HTTP/2 connection injection over upgraded sockets, showing deep understanding of the HTTP/2 protocol negotiation flow
Modified ssl_wrapper.zig to fix TLS behavior and properly handle server-side duplex upgrades with correct ALPN and handshake direction semantics
Added comprehensive test coverage (428 lines) including HTTP/1→HTTP/2 upgrade scenarios, demonstrating understanding of real-world protocol upgrade edge cases
expertise_classifications.summary: Introduces a new SocketMode abstraction to properly distinguish duplex-upgraded TLS servers from listener-owned servers, fixes SSLWrapper behavior, and adds HTTP/2 connection injection support — demonstrating architect-level understanding of the TLS/HTTP2 protocol stack and socket lifecycle management across native and JS layers.

expertise_classifications.author: dylan-conway
expertise_signals: Understands cross-compilation toolchain intricacies: correctly setting CMAKE_C_COMPILER_TARGET, CMAKE_CROSSCOMPILING, and architecture-specific linker paths (Hostx64/arm64 vs HostARM64/arm64)
Handles edge cases in BoringSSL ASM incompatibility on Windows ARM64 by disabling ASM to avoid mixing non-ARM object files into ARM64 libs
Knows to skip post-build test/feature steps when cross-compiling since target binaries can't run on the host, and conditionally excludes features.json from bunFiles
Fixes highway_strings.cpp with platform-specific intrinsic guards (#if defined(__ARM_NEON) vs HWY_ARCH_X86) showing understanding of SIMD portability across architectures
expertise_classifications.summary: Fixes Windows ARM64 cross-compilation CI by correcting toolchain configuration, disabling incompatible ASM in BoringSSL, setting proper cargo cross-compile targets for lolhtml, guarding architecture-specific SIMD intrinsics, and skipping host-incompatible post-build steps — demonstrating deep understanding of cross-compilation constraints across multiple build systems.

expertise_classifications.author: robobun
expertise_signals: Changed pg_hba.conf from localhost-only (127.0.0.1/32, ::1/128) to container-accessible CIDR ranges (0.0.0.0/0, ::/0) with added local socket rules for init scripts - shows understanding of Docker networking constraints
Added 'local all postgres trust' and 'local all all trust' entries before hostssl entries, understanding that pg_hba.conf order matters and init scripts need local socket access

Switched from volume-mounting certs into a stock postgres image to a custom Dockerfile build, with corresponding changes to docker-compose, the build helper, and the test file - a coordinated multi-file infrastructure change
Increased start_period from 5s to 60s and added start_interval: 1s, indicating awareness that custom-built containers with init scripts take longer to become healthy
expertise_classifications.summary: Migrates TLS PostgreSQL tests from external secret-based URLs to a locally-built Docker container, requiring coordinated changes across Docker configuration, build infrastructure, pg_hba networking rules, and test code - demonstrating deep understanding of PostgreSQL auth, Docker networking, and test infrastructure constraints.

expertise_classifications.author: cirospaciari
expertise_signals: Extracted isNoProxy into a reusable public function from previously inlined logic, enabling consistent NO_PROXY enforcement across both fetch and WebSocket code paths
Correctly handles the semantic difference between proxy: '' (explicitly no proxy) vs proxy: someUrl (explicit proxy that should still respect NO_PROXY)
Added C FFI bridge (Bun__isNoProxy) to expose Zig NO_PROXY logic to C++ WebSocket code, understanding the cross-language boundary architecture
Comprehensive test coverage for both fetch and WebSocket proxy scenarios, including edge cases like NO_PROXY=* and hostname matching with ports
expertise_classifications.summary: Fixes NO_PROXY environment variable being ignored when explicit proxy options are provided to fetch() and WebSocket, requiring refactoring the NO_PROXY check into a shared function and bridging it across Zig/C++ boundaries, demonstrating deep understanding of the proxy resolution architecture.

pattern_result.executive_summary: Bun's codebase has a severe review culture problem: human reviewers rubber-stamp virtually all PRs—including architect-level changes—while the only substantive review comes from bots (coderabbitai). The core module src/bun.js has a dangerously low bus factor (0.11), and multiple critical modules depend on contributors who've gone silent. Knowledge is concentrated in 3-4 people with no meaningful cross-review happening between them.

insights.title: Human code review is effectively non-existent
insights.description: Across all 99 PRs analyzed, every single human review (Jarred-Sumner, dylan-conway, alii, sosukesuzuki, cirospaciari) was classified as rubber_stamp with empty comments. Jarred-Sumner rubber-stamped PR#26539 (+9142 lines, architect-level TLS/HTTP2 rewrite), PR#26402 (+2598 lines, ESM bytecode across entire pipeline), PR#26440 (his own markdown parser reviewed by others who also rubber-stamped), and PR#26436 (TC39 decorators). The ONLY substantive reviews come from coderabbitai bot. The team has no human review culture—bots are the last line of defense against bugs shipping.

insights.title: src/ast is a single-person module with 95% ownership by an infrequent contributor
insights.description: pfg@pfg.pw owns 95% of src/ast blame but contributed only 3 commits in 3 months (+7826/-163 lines—large but infrequent bulk changes). The AST module is foundational to the transpiler and bundler. The remaining 5% is split between contact@taylor.fish (2%) and zackradisic (2%), neither of whom appear as active contributors. If pfg becomes unavailable, nobody on the current active team can maintain the AST layer that the entire compilation pipeline depends on.

insights.title: Two ghost owners hold 36% of the core src/bun.js module
insights.description: git@paperclover.net owns 25% of src/bun.js (the project's central module with 1060 commits and bus_factor=0.11) but does not appear in the top 15 contributors for the last 3 months. Similarly, this person owns 11% of src/bundler. Combined with Jarred's 40%, these two people control 65% of the core module's knowledge. If paperclover has already left, 25% of institutional knowledge in the most critical module is unrecoverable without archaeology.

insights.title: src/bundler's majority owner zackradisic (59%) has zero recent activity
insights.description: 56137411+zackradisic@users.noreply.github.com owns 59% of src/bundler blame but doesn't appear in the top contributors list for the past 3 months. The next owners are Jarred (15%) and paperclover (11%, also inactive). The bundler—a core differentiator for Bun—has no active contributor who holds majority knowledge. Recent bundler work appears to be done by Jarred and robobun, who together own only ~15% of the module's history.

insights.title: robobun is not a bot—it's a prolific human contributor masquerading as automation
insights.description: robobun@oven.sh has 202 commits (41% of all commits) and is classified with 'deep' expertise on security fixes (null byte injection in SQL, CRLF header injection, chunked transfer encoding hardening), use-after-free GC bugs, and highly complex feature work (--metafile-md). No CI bot writes security patches for HTTP request smuggling or fixes WebSocket GC lifecycle bugs. This is likely a team member (or multiple members) committing under a shared account, which obscures true ownership and makes bus factor calculations unreliable for every module robobun touches.

insights.title: claude AI reviewer provides literally zero value across all reviewed PRs
insights.description: The 'claude' reviewer left rubber_stamp reviews with completely empty comment bodies on PR#26248, PR#26539 (3 empty comments), PR#26551 (4 empty comments), PR#26703, and PR#26594 (7 empty comments). That's 17 empty review comments across 5 PRs—including architect-level changes to the TLS/HTTP2 stack and the multi-script execution system. This tool is creating false confidence that reviews are happening while adding zero signal.

insights.title: Alistair Smith (alii) is an emerging architect being underutilized in review
insights.description: alii authored PR#26402 (architect-level ESM bytecode compilation across the entire pipeline: bundler, linker, runtime, standalone graph, C++ bindings) and has 21% ownership of bun-types, yet his only review activity is rubber-stamping (PR#23995, PR#26402 self, PR#26439). He works across src/OutputFile.zig, src/StandaloneModuleGraph.zig, src/analyze_transpiled_module.zig, src/ast, and src/bake—touching 5+ critical modules. He's a natural cross-pollinator who should be reviewing bundler and compiler changes.

insights.title: Mutual rubber-stamp ring between core maintainers
insights.description: Jarred-Sumner approves dylan-conway's PRs with no comments (and vice versa: dylan-conway rubber-stamped PR#26551 and PR#26440). Jarred also rubber-stamps cirospaciari (PR#26539), sosukesuzuki (PR#26380), alii (PR#26402), and robobun (PR#26441). In every case, the approval has zero review content. This creates a knowledge silo where the 3-4 core maintainers each work in isolation with ceremonial approvals, meaning nobody actually understands each other's complex changes.

insights.title: SUZUKI Sosuke is a high-value cross-pollinator bridging runtime performance and testing infrastructure
insights.description: sosukesuzuki works across JSC JIT stress testing (PR#26380), native C++ Buffer performance (PR#26819), structuredClone optimization (PR#26818), and CI architecture (PR#26589 QEMU JIT testing). He uniquely bridges performance-critical native code with test infrastructure—two domains that rarely overlap. With 30 commits spanning src/bun.js, bench/snippets, test/js, src/js, and cmake/tools, he's one of the few contributors with both deep JSC internals knowledge and CI expertise.

insights.title: Suspicious contributor email mismatch: Przemysław Rekucki using alistair@anthropic.com
insights.description: Contributor 'Przemysław Rekucki' has their email listed as 'alistair@anthropic.com', which is clearly mismatched—either a git config error, an attribution issue, or commits made from a shared/misconfigured environment. This person authored PR#23995 (a deep HMR race condition fix touching critical hot-reload infrastructure). If attribution is wrong, the actual author's knowledge is invisible to bus factor analysis, and the wrong person gets credit in blame.

recommendations: Immediately establish a mandatory review policy: architect-level PRs (>500 lines touching core modules) require at least one human reviewer who leaves substantive comments before merge.
Audit who commits as robobun—if it's a shared account, split into individual accounts to restore accurate ownership tracking and bus factor calculations.
Remove or reconfigure the claude reviewer integration; it produces only empty comments and creates false review coverage signals.
Schedule knowledge transfer sessions from Jarred and paperclover to dylan-conway and sosukesuzuki on src/bun.js internals to raise bus factor above 0.20.
Assign alii as a required reviewer on src/bundler and src/ast changes—he already touches adjacent modules and can bridge the knowledge gap left by zackradisic's departure.
Create onboarding documentation for src/ast and src/bundler before pfg and zackradisic's knowledge becomes fully inaccessible.
Pair sosukesuzuki with cirospaciari on HTTP/network code reviews—Sosuke's testing rigor would complement Ciro's protocol expertise and break their respective silos.
